{
  "block": 1,
  "unit": 1,
  "type": "grammar",
  "unitTitle": "Unit 1: Present simple, present continuous, stative verbs",
  "sections": [
    {
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Present simple",
      "content": [
        {
          "subtitle": "Form",
          "rows": [
            {
              "label": "statement",
              "left": "I/you/we/they **play** ...",
              "right": "He/she/it **plays** ..."
            },
            {
              "label": "negative",
              "left": "I/you/we/they **do not (don't) play** ...",
              "right": "He/she/it **does not (doesn't) play** ..."
            },
            {
              "label": "question",
              "left": "**Do** I/you/we/they **play** ...?",
              "right": "**Does** he/she/it **play** ...?"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "subtitle": "Use",
          "items": [
            "Present habits",
            "Permanent situations",
            "States",
            "General truths"
          ]
        },
        {
          "subtitle": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "Marsha **goes** to dance lessons every Saturday.",
            "Dan **works** at the cinema.",
            "I **like** the new James Bond film.",
            "You **play** chess with 32 pieces."
          ]
        },
        {
          "subtitle": "Helpful hints",
          "items": [
            "always, usually, often",
            "sometimes, rarely, never",
            "every Monday/week/etc",
            "once/twice a week/month/etc",
            "three times a week/month/etc",
            "These adverbs usually go before the verb, but after the verb **be**."
          ]
        },
        {
          "subtitle": "Watch out!",
          "notes": [
            "The verbs **be** and **have** have irregular present forms."
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Present continuous",
      "content": [
        {
          "subtitle": "Form",
          "rows": [
            {
              "label": "statement",
              "left": "I **am ('m) playing** ...",
              "right": "He/she/it **is ('s) playing** ... You/we/they **are ('re) playing** ..."
            },
            {
              "label": "negative",
              "left": "I **am not ('m not) playing** ...",
              "right": "He/she/it **is not (isn't / 's not) playing** ... You/we/they **are not (aren't / 're not) playing** ..."
            },
            {
              "label": "question",
              "left": "**Am** I **playing** ...?",
              "right": "**Is** he/she/it **playing** ...? **Are** you/we/they **playing** ...?"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "subtitle": "Use",
          "items": [
            "Actions happening now",
            "Temporary situations",
            "Annoying habits (usually with always)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "subtitle": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "Jan **is watching** a DVD upstairs.",
            "She **is working** at the museum until the end of the month.",
            "My brother **is always borrowing** my CDs without asking!"
          ]
        },
        {
          "subtitle": "Helpful hints",
          "items": [
            "now",
            "right now",
            "at the moment",
            "today",
            "this week/month/etc"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Stative verbs",
      "content": [
        {
          "subtitle": "Form",
          "description": "Stative verbs do not usually describe actions. They describe states (feelings, thoughts, etc). They are not normally used in continuous tenses.",
          "items": [
            "✓ I **like** reading books in my free time.",
            "✗ I **am liking** reading books in my free time."
          ]
        },
        {
          "subtitle": "Some common stative verbs",
          "chipStyle": true,
          "items": [
            "appear",
            "be",
            "believe",
            "belong to",
            "hate",
            "have",
            "include",
            "know",
            "like",
            "love",
            "need",
            "prefer",
            "see",
            "seem",
            "taste",
            "think",
            "understand",
            "want"
          ]
        },
        {
          "subtitle": "Watch out!",
          "notes": [
            "Some stative verbs (such as **be**, **have** and **think**) are used in continuous tenses when they describe actions.",
            "What do you **think** about his new song?",
            "I'**m thinking** about last night's match."
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
